<h2>California Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>California offers some of the nation's most generous incentive programs for solar panels and energy-efficient HVAC systems. The federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, with the credit stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the entire cost of solar installation, including equipment, labor, and permitting fees, making it one of the most valuable incentives available to California homeowners.</p>

<p>The Self-Generation Incentive Program (SGIP) provides substantial rebates for energy storage systems, offering up to \$1,000 per kilowatt-hour of installed battery capacity. Low-income customers and those in high fire-threat districts can receive enhanced incentives up to \$1,000 per kWh. SGIP has allocated over \$1.2 billion for energy storage projects, making California the nation's largest residential battery storage market. The program also supports fuel cells and other advanced energy technologies with similar rebate structures.</p>

<p>PG&E, Southern California Edison, and San Diego Gas & Electric offer various rebate programs for high-efficiency HVAC equipment. PG&E's Energy Efficiency Rebates provide up to \$3,000 for qualifying heat pump installations and \$1,500 for high-efficiency air conditioning systems. Additional rebates are available for smart thermostats (\$75-\$125), duct sealing services (\$400-\$600), and whole-house fans (\$200-\$400). The California Alternative Rates for Energy (CARE) program provides additional discounts for qualified low-income customers, reducing electricity bills by 30-35%.</p>

<p>Local utility districts and municipalities often provide additional incentive layers. Sacramento Municipal Utility District (SMUD) offers SolarShares programs and additional HVAC rebates. Many cities provide expedited permitting for solar installations and reduced permit fees. Property tax exclusions ensure that solar installations don't increase property tax assessments, while net metering programs provide ongoing credits for excess solar production. These combined incentives can reduce total system costs by 40-60% for qualified installations.</p>

